"{\"uid\": \"thesouthafrican.com-sport-paris-olympics-2024-paris-olympics-2024-team-south-africa-to-have-one-medal-winner-prediction-breaking-news-free-to-read-sports-illustrated-result\", \"text\": \"Copyright Blue Sky Publications (Pty) Ltd. All Rights Reserved.  thesouthafrican.com is a division of Blue Sky Publications Ltd. Reproduction without permission prohibited  Home\\u00bbSport\\u00bbParis Olympics 2024\\u00bbParis Olympics 2024: Team SA to have ONE medal winner - PREDICTION  Team South Africa\\u00a0will be represented by a total number of\\u00a0138\\u00a0athletes in\\u00a0a record 19\\u00a0different sporting codes at the Paris Olympics 2024.  Although theParis Olympics 2024only officially begins at Friday's opening ceremony, competition for medals will get underway onWednesday, 24 July.  That'sTODAY!  For the latest Paris Olympics 2024 news, bookmarkThe South African website'sdedicated section  Rugby sevensandfootballwill kick off the action at what is officially theGames of the XXXIII Olympiadand officially branded asParis 2024.  As was first reported byThe South African website,Team SAwill be represented by a total number of138athletes in\\u00a0a record19different sporting codes.  The squad also hasninereserves for a number of the different codes.  Team SA has won38medals (11 gold, 18 silver, nine bronze) since readmission to the Olympic fold at the 1992 Barcelona Games - and89(27 gold, 33 silver, 29 bronze) since the country first competed in St. Louis in 1904.  This will be South Africa'sninthconsecutive appearance at the Olympics since readmission and Mzansi's21stoverall appearance.  How will South African fare this time around in Paris?  Respected American websiteSports Illustratedhas predicted the winner ofeverygold, silver and bronze medal that will be awarded in329events from 26 July to 11 August.  OnlyONETeam SA athlete, swimmerTatjana Smith(n\\u00e9eSchoenmaker), features as a predicted medal winner.  Sports Illustratedhas Smith defending her women's200m breaststroketitle from the 2020 Tokyo Olympics, as well as finishing as runner-up in the women's100m breaststroke- as she did in Japan.  Gold:Tang Qianting (China)Silver:Tatjana Smith (South Africa)Bronze:Lilly King (USA)  Gold:Tatjana Smith (South Africa)Silver:Kate Douglass (USA)Bronze:Tes Schouten (Netherlands)  Should Smith pick up a gold and a silver in Paris, as per the South African Sports Confederation and Olympic Committee's (Sascoc) financial incentives, she would pocketR400 000(for gold) andR200 000(for silver).  Smith's coach,Rocco Meiring, would also be in the money, to the tune ofR100 000andR50 000, respectively.  While there might be an argument thatSport Illustrated'sreporting may be biased, time will tell how many South Africans do step onto the podium in France.  The South African websitewill keep readers up-to-date with unparalleledFREEcoverage of every South African performance and result.  Why pay when you can read for free?  Final additions to the squad have been made and the names of those added have an asterisk (*) next to them.  AQUATICS (9)Men (3):Pieter Coetze (100m, 200m backstroke), Chad le Clos (100m butterfly), Matthew Sates (100m, 200m butterfly and 200m IM)Women (6):Aimee Canny (200m freestyle), Kaylene Corbett (200m breaststroke), Erin Gallagher (100m butterfly), Rebecca Meder (200m IM), Tatjana Smith (100m, 200m breaststroke), Julia Vincent (diving, 3m springboard)Management:Rocco Meiring, Chanelle van Wyk, Dean Price, Mafata Modutoane  ARCHERY (1)Men:Wian Roux (recurve)Coach/Manager:Patrick Roux  ATHLETICS (34)Men (23):*Kyle Blignaut (shot put), *Edmund du Plessis (800m), Elroy Galant (marathon), *Victor Hogan (discus), Gardeo Isaacs (4x400m), *Cheswill Johnson (long jump), Shaun Maswangani (100m, 200m, 4x100m), Stephen Mokoka (marathon), *Ryan Mphalele (1 500m), Zakithi Nene (400m, 4x400m), Bradley Nkoana (4x100m), Antonie Nortje (4x400m), Lythe Pillay (400m, 4x400m), Francois Prinsloo (discus), *Brian Raats (high jump